  <p>
A 
    <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_community">Community</xref>
Â is a 
    <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_geographic_area">GEOGRAPHIC AREA</xref>
.  </p>
  <p>
      <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_community">Community</xref>
 is a very general term referring to the people living in a locality or to the locality itself.  </p>
  <p>
      <i>
Note: Welsh 
      <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_community">Communities</xref>
 are subdivisions of 
      <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authorities</xref>
 and their councils are the most local level of government in Wales. They are the equivalent of (civil) 
      <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_parish">Parishes</xref>
 in England, but unlike English 
      <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_parish">Parishes</xref>
, 
      <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_community">Communities</xref>
 cover the whole of Wales.    </i>
  </p>
  <p>
For further information on 
    <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_community">Communities</xref>
, see the 
    <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
            keyref="business_definition_office_for_national_statistics">Office for National Statistics</xref>
 website at: 
    <xref href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/census/2001censusandearlier/glossary/ou"
            scope="external"
            format="html">Glossary</xref>
.  </p>

